Import Data

The following is a datset of tree around New York

treeData <- read.csv("data/2015_Street_Tree_Census_-_Tree_Data.csv")
treeData <- treeData[,c("spc_common", "latitude", "longitude", "borough", "nta_name")]

species <- treeData %>% 
  group_by(spc_common) %>% 
  summarise(n = n())
species
## # A tibble: 133 × 2
##    spc_common                   n
##    <chr>                    <int>
##  1 ""                       31619
##  2 "'Schubert' chokecherry"  4888
##  3 "American beech"           273
##  4 "American elm"            7975
##  5 "American hophornbeam"    1081
##  6 "American hornbeam"       1517
##  7 "American larch"            46
##  8 "American linden"        13530
##  9 "Amur cork tree"           183
## 10 "Amur maackia"            2197
## # … with 123 more rows
ggplot(species, aes(x = reorder(spc_common, n), y = n)) + 
  geom_col() + labs(x = "Species", y = "Count") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

boroughs <- treeData %>% 
  group_by(borough) %>% 
  summarise(n = n())
boroughs
## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   borough            n
##   <chr>          <int>
## 1 Bronx          85203
## 2 Brooklyn      177293
## 3 Manhattan      65423
## 4 Queens        250551
## 5 Staten Island 105318
ggplot(boroughs, aes(x = reorder(borough, n), y = n)) + 
  geom_col() + labs(x = "Borough", y = "Count") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

zipCodes <- treeData %>% 
  group_by(nta_name) %>% 
  summarise(n = n())
zipCodes
## # A tibble: 188 × 2
##    nta_name                                       n
##    <chr>                                      <int>
##  1 Allerton-Pelham Gardens                     3843
##  2 Annadale-Huguenot-Prince's Bay-Eltingville 12969
##  3 Arden Heights                               6999
##  4 Astoria                                     4393
##  5 Auburndale                                  5332
##  6 Baisley Park                                4815
##  7 Bath Beach                                  1818
##  8 Battery Park City-Lower Manhattan           1311
##  9 Bay Ridge                                   7026
## 10 Bayside-Bayside Hills                       9780
## # … with 178 more rows
ggplot(zipCodes, aes(x = reorder(nta_name, n), y = n)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  labs(x = "Zip Code", y = "Count") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

Import Data

Reducing the dataset and only parsing geospatial data allows us to feed it into maps to visualize the distribution of trees. It’s also possible for us to plot the distribution by type so that we can understand the concentration of species on a borough and even zip code level.
